# Here Comes the Rain Again

"Here Comes the Rain Again" is a 1983 song by the British duo [Eurythmics](/Eurythmics), serving as the opening track from their third studio album [Touch](/Touch_(Eurythmics_album)). Written by group members [Annie Lennox](/Annie_Lennox) and [David A. Stewart](/David_A._Stewart), and produced by Stewart, the song was released on 13 January 1984 as the album's third single in the UK and the first single in the United States. It became Eurythmics' second top 10 U.S. hit, peaking at number four on the [Billboard Hot 100](/Billboard_Hot_100), and hit number eight in the [UK Singles Chart](/UK_Singles_Chart), becoming their fifth consecutive top 10 single in their home country.

## Background and Composition

The song's creation is steeped in a blend of melancholy and artistic innovation. Stewart, known for his ability to craft emotionally resonant compositions, explained to [Songfacts](/Songfacts) that the song's mood is a mixture of minor and major tonalities, creating a sense of suspended melancholy. He described it as "a weird course," capturing the essence of depression and the downward spiral, yet intertwined with moments of dark beauty. The song's lyrical content, with lines like "talk to me like lovers do," wanders in and out of melancholy, evoking imagery of a rose unfolding in the darkest hour before the garden dies.

The song was written during a stay at the [Mayflower Hotel](/15_Central_Park_West) in New York City. On an overcast day, Stewart was playing melancholic chords on his Casio keyboard, incorporating a B note into an A minor progression. Lennox, inspired by the gray skies and the New York skyline, spontaneously sang the line "Here comes the rain again," which became the foundation for the rest of the song.

## Recording and Production

The recording process for "Here Comes the Rain Again" was notable for its innovative use of space and orchestration. The string arrangements by [Michael Kamen](/Michael_Kamen) were performed by members of the British Philharmonic Orchestra. Due to the limited space in [The Church Studios](/The_Church_Studios), the musicians had to record their parts in various locations throughout the facility. The cellists were positioned in a corridor leading to a door, while the violinists and violists were situated in the facility's kitchen and bathroom, respectively. Wires and microphones were installed throughout the studio and connected to a [Soundcraft](/Soundcraft) mixing console located at the top of a [spiral staircase](/Stairs).

The song was mixed by blending the orchestral tracks with the original synthesized backing track, which included programmed drums and sequencers. Stewart also played parts on a [Gretsch](/Gretsch) Country Club guitar with a [Bigsby tremolo arm](/Bigsby_vibrato_tailpiece). The final mix resulted in a rich, layered sound that combined electronic and orchestral elements seamlessly.

## Release and Reception

"Here Comes the Rain Again" was released to critical and commercial acclaim. During the week of 28 January 1984, [Billboard](/Billboard_(magazine)) announced that the song was the second most added track to Hot 100 reporting stations in the United States. In the UK, the single became Eurythmics' fifth Top 10 hit, peaking at number eight. It was the duo's second top ten hit in the United States, reaching number four in March 1984.

[Cashbox](/Cashbox_(magazine)) praised the song, noting that Lennox's vocals were "familiarly sultry and wispy," while Stewart's composition was laced with pizzicato strings and chiming, open chord guitar work. The song's success was further cemented by its strong performance on various charts, including reaching number one in Venezuela and achieving top 20 positions in several other countries.

## Music Video

The music video for "Here Comes the Rain Again" was directed by Stewart, Jonathan Gershfield, and Jon Roseman, and filmed in December 1983. The video opens with an aerial shot of the [Old Man of Hoy](/Old_Man_of_Hoy) on the Island of [Hoy](/Hoy,_Orkney) in the [Orkney Islands](/Orkney) before transitioning to Lennox walking along the rocky shore and cliff top. She later explores a derelict cottage while wearing a nightgown and holding a lantern. Stewart stalks her with a video camera, and in many scenes, the two are filmed separately and then superimposed into the same frame.

